      "title": "Why Adaptive Learning Rates?",
      "key_message": "Static learning rates fail to balance convergence speed and generalisation.",
      "layout_type": "title_content",
      "background_color": null,
      "footer_override": null,
      "text_elements": [
        {
          "element_id": "s002_title",
          "role": "title",
          "content": "Why Adaptive Learning Rates?",
          "position": { "x": 2.0, "y": 0.5, "w": 29.87, "h": 2.0 },
          "style": {
            "font_size": 28,
            "bold": true,
            "color": "#1F3864",
            "align": "left"
          },
          "z_index": 0
        },
        {
          "element_id": "s002_body",
          "role": "body",
          "content": "• Static learning rates require manual tuning per task\n• Too high → unstable training (loss diverges)\n• Too low → slow convergence and underfitting\n• Adaptive methods automatically adjust the rate per parameter\n• Key challenge: fast convergence vs. good generalisation",
          "position": { "x": 2.0, "y": 3.2, "w": 29.87, "h": 14.3 },
          "style": {
            "font_size": 20,
            "bold": false,
            "color": "#000000",
            "align": "left"
          },
          "z_index": 1
        },
        {
          "element_id": "s002_caption",
          "role": "caption",
          "content": "Wilson et al. (2017): Adaptive methods may generalise worse than SGD on some tasks.",
          "position": { "x": 2.0, "y": 16.8, "w": 29.87, "h": 0.9 },
          "style": {
            "font_size": 13,
            "bold": false,
            "italic": true,
